  "prompt": "Why are speed bumps bad?",
  "response": "Speed bumps can have several drawbacks:\n\n1. Vehicle damage\n- Can cause wear and tear on suspension systems\n- Risk of damaging low-profile vehicles\n- Potential alignment issues\n\n2. Increased vehicle wear\n- Repeated jarring can damage car components\n- Higher fuel consumption due to slowing down and accelerating\n\n3. Emergency vehicle concerns\n- Slow down ambulances, fire trucks, and police vehicles\n- Potential delays in critical response times\n\n4. Noise and vibration\n- Create disruptive noise when vehicles pass over\n- Cause uncomfortable vibrations for passengers\n\n5. Traffic flow issues\n- Reduce overall road efficiency\n- Cause unnecessary stopping and starting\n\n6. Environmental impact\n- Increased vehicle emissions from repeated braking and acceleration\n- More fuel consumption\n\n7. Potential road maintenance challenges\n- Require regular maintenance\n- Can deteriorate over time, creating additional road hazards\n\n8. Uneven road surface\n- Can create drainage problems\n- May collect water or debris\n\nWhile speed bumps are intended to improve safety by slowing traffic, they can create multiple secondary problems for drivers and communities.",
